[1] Russia, poultry
Date: Mon 31 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ria novosti, 31 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://en.rian.ru/russia/20051031/41947616.html>

Bird flu confirmed in 10 rural communities across Russia
-----------------------------------------------
Suspected cases of avian influenza have now been confirmed in 10
rural communities across Russia and are being verified in 19 others,
the Agriculture Ministry said in a press release Monday [31 Oct
2005]. The confirmed outbreak sites are in the central regions of
Tula and Tambov, as well as in the Urals province of Chelyabinsk and
in Omsk and Altai, in Siberia. [Map at
<http://www.eegas.com/images/11-legend.gif>].
Russia's Kurgan region is the worst affected, with 3 confirmed
outbreak sites and 3 suspected. In the Novosibirsk province, 16
communities are currently under suspicion.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A separate newswire of Ria Novosti, 31 Oct 2005, says:
"Mass deaths of migrant birds have been registered outside
Yekaterinburg, the Urals, a spokesman for the local consumer
protection service said Monday [31 Oct 2005].
"Late last week, dead waxwings were found in Asbest [a local town],"
the spokesman said, adding that samples had been taken and sent for
examination. The results will be ready Wednesday [2 Nov 2005], the
representative said."
Waxwings belong to Order: Passeriformes, Family: Bombycillidae,
Genus: _Bombycilla_. Details on the identity of the species involved
are requested; see following items. - Mod.AS]
******
[2] Romania, wild birds
Date: Mon 31 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ITN, 31 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.itn.co.uk/news/497473.html>

More bird flu cases found in Romania
-------------------------------------------
Chief veterinarian Ion Agafitei said a goose and a swan had both
tested positive for the H5 type of bird flu.
He said it had not yet been decided whether to send the samples to
the UK to see whether they had the virulent H5N1 strain.
Earlier this month [October 2005], the Balkan state became the 1st
country in mainland Europe to detect the deadly H5N1 virus in poultry
in 2 villages in the Danube delta, Europe's largest wetlands.
A heron carrying the strain was also found near the border with Moldova.
"We found a wild goose near the village of Vadu Oii and a swan next
to the Razim lake, which were tested positive for H5," Mr. Agafitei said.
The areas will not be quarantined as the birds were found at least
one mile from the nearest human settlement, and no poultry will be culled.
Vadu Oii lies close to the Danube river in Constanta county [at
Giurgeni in the map
<http://www.ici.ro/romania/images/turism/r_constanta.jpg>],
while Razim is the biggest lake in the delta near the Black Sea,
which wild birds use to rest on their way to warmer climes [see map
<http://www.ici.ro/romania/images/turism/r_tulcea.jpg>].
The areas are roughly 44 miles [70 km] from each other.
Romanian authorities have said over 500 tests were done over the past
2 weeks on birds in the country's southeast, and they all turned out
negative for bird flu.
The deadly strain was found in samples taken from 2 villages in the
Danube delta earlier in October 2005. Over 21 000 domestic birds in
the 2 villages, which were quarantined, were culled.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Information on the exact identities (species) of the 2 birds
involved -- a goose and a swan (unspecified) -- is requested; see the
